\begin_layout Standard
The proof is by contradiction: Suppose there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-deterministic QIVPM
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}:\events\rightarrow\mathscr{I}$
\end_inset

.
 Now use this assumed QIVPM to construct the following 0-deterministic QIVPM
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}^{\textrm{D}}:\events\rightarrow\left\{ \imposs,\necess\right\} $
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\mu}^{\textrm{D}}\left(P\right)=\begin{cases}
\imposs\,, & \textrm{ if }\bar{\mu}\left(P\right)\subseteq\left[0,\delta\right]\:;\\
\necess\,, & \textrm{ if }\bar{\mu}\left(P\right)\subseteq\left[1-\delta,1\right]\:.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

However, since we know that 0-deterministic QIVPMs do not exist, the map
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}^{\textrm{D}}$
\end_inset

 cannot exist and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}$
\end_inset

 does not exist.
 It remains to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}^{\textrm{D}}$
\end_inset

 is indeed a 0-deterministic QIVPM by checking that for orthogonal projectors
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}^{\textrm{D}}\left(P_{0}\right)=\bar{\mu}^{\textrm{D}}\left(P_{1}\right)=\imposs$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}^{\textrm{D}}\left(P_{0}+P_{1}\right)=\imposs$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TaiThesis2018"

\end_inset

.
 Indeed when 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}^{\textrm{D}}\left(P_{0}\right)=\bar{\mu}^{\textrm{D}}\left(P_{1}\right)=\imposs$
\end_inset

, we have both 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(P_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(P_{1}\right)\subseteq\left[0,\delta\right]$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(P_{0}+P_{1}\right)\subseteq\left[0,2\delta\right]$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta<\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $2\delta<1-\delta$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(P_{0}+P_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 cannot be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1-\delta,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(P_{0}+P_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a subset of either 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\delta\right]$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1-\delta,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and the latter is excluded, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(P_{0}+P_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 must be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\delta\right]$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}^{\textrm{D}}\left(P_{0}+P_{1}\right)=\imposs$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the theorem holds when 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta<\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

